       <h2 class="entry-header font-entryheader">
           
        <span class="entry-title">
<a href="https://www.securityskeptic.com/2020/05/online-child-predation-rising-during-covid-lockdown-.html">Online child predation rising during COVID lockdown </a>
        </span>
       </h2>



       <h5 class="date-header font-dateheader">
           <span class="entry-date"><a href="https://www.securityskeptic.com/2020/05/online-child-predation-rising-during-covid-lockdown-.html">Tuesday, 26 May 2020</a></span>
       </h5>



			<div class="entry-body font-entrybody">
				<p>I attended (remotely) a Council of Europe cybercrime webinar on the impact of COVID on cybercrime last week. One of the most disturbing criminal activities discussed was the rise in reports of online predation.</p>
<p>The National Center for Missing and Exploited Children (NCMEC) has received 4.2 million reports in April. That’s up 2 million from March 2020 and nearly 3 million from April 2019. (Forbes, 9 May 2020).</p>
<div class="text_exposed_show">
<p>This is not surprising - nearly everyone who is connected is spending more time on the Internet - but it&#39;s still terrifying.</p>
<p>Look to the many government agencies have parental guidelines to help identify child abuse, exploitation or grooming.</p>
<p>The US FBI (<a data-ft="{&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;-U&quot;}" data-lynx-mode="async" data-lynx-uri="https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.fbi.gov%2Finvestigate%2Fviolent-crime%2Fcac%3Ffbclid%3DIwAR0gPoKjsQ5nh-JTcK4QAeGOrRWOpFR21mZXW8jvViq5DLXD54IlSzHCus8&amp;h=AT3eYirKN9c8y6ZPMNT9eYl5e0FRZG7v2_ctkIISBnNX-9uC8djHUq1HlZAN7Fy7RaHyrBDhiGO6FJGGLbTmkFU7d_JLULuNnZGZgCthcDoHkj4srqb8I2ZnIR61r93ZzWeaN73893fhIbhjNQ25WnOUmScEvU3jQC45Uab6KA" href="https://www.fbi.gov/investigate/violent-crime/cac?fbclid=IwAR0gPoKjsQ5nh-JTcK4QAeGOrRWOpFR21mZXW8jvViq5DLXD54IlSzHCus8" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">https://www.fbi.gov/investigate/violent-crime/cac</a>) has information about grooming, trafficking, sextortion and other abuses. In the UK, the NCA (<a href="https://nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/what-we-do/crime-threats/child-sexual-abuse-and-exploitation">https://nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/what-we-do/crime-threats/child-sexual-abuse-and-exploitation</a>) offers similar information</p>
<p>The US DHA (<a href="https://www.dhs.gov/blog/2011/08/09/protect-your-kids-cyber-predators">https://www.dhs.gov/blog/2011/08/09/protect-your-kids-cyber-predators</a>) shares tips for parents. I also found a helpful guidelines report from UK West Midlands (<a href="https://www.local.gov.uk/sites/default/files/documents/safeguarding-children-and-c8c.pdf">https://www.local.gov.uk/sites/default/files/documents/safeguarding-children-and-c8c.pdf</a>). And you&#39;ll find additional information at Stop.Think.Connect Parent and Educator resources (<a href="https://www.cisa.gov/publication/stopthinkconnect-parent-and-educator-resources">https://www.cisa.gov/publication/stopthinkconnect-parent-and-educator-resources</a>).</p>
<p>&#0160;</p>
</div>
			</div>
			

			





